How to Start Vibe Coding

(Even If You've Never Written a Line of Code)

Look, I'm going to save you hours of research here.

Vibe coding is basically this: you describe what you want in plain English, and AI writes the code for you. That's it. You don't need to know Python or JavaScript or whatever. You just need to be able to explain what you're trying to build.

And honestly? It works way better than you'd expect.

The 60-Second Explanation

Here's the thing about vibe coding. It's not magic. It's more like having a really fast junior developer who never gets tired and never judges your dumb questions.

You tell it what you want. It builds it. You tell it what's wrong. It fixes it.

The term comes from this idea of just "vibing" with the AI, trusting it to figure out the technical stuff while you focus on the vision. Some people take this too far and never look at the code. Probably not ideal. But for getting started? It's actually pretty freeing.

Where to Actually Learn This

Forget the $500 courses. Here's what's free and actually good:

Vibe Coding 101 with Replit on DeepLearning.ai. It's a short course. Takes maybe an afternoon. Gets you building real things immediately.

Claude Code in Action on Anthropic's Skilljar. This one's specifically for Claude, which is what a lot of people end up using anyway.

Microsoft's Generative AI for Beginners on GitHub. More comprehensive if you want the bigger picture.

That's it. You don't need five courses. Pick one, finish it, then start building something real. The learning happens in the doing.

The Basic Workflow That Actually Works

I've seen people overcomplicate this. Here's what tends to work:

First, figure out what you're building. Not vaguely. Specifically. "I want an app that tracks my daily water intake and reminds me to drink" is good. "I want to build something cool" is useless.

Then, write it out. Some people call this a technical design document. That sounds fancy. Really it's just... writing down what you want. What should happen when someone opens the app? What buttons are there? What does it look like?

You can even use AI for this part. Tell Claude or Gemini what you're thinking, and ask it to help you organize your thoughts into a clear plan.

Now take that plan to your coding tool. Cursor and Claude Code are the popular ones right now. Feed it your plan. Let it build.

Here's the key part: go one step at a time.

Don't ask it to build the whole app at once. Ask it to build the home screen. Check it. Then ask for the next piece. This keeps things from going off the rails.

Mistakes That'll Waste Your Time and Money

I've seen these enough times that they're worth calling out.

Paying for tokens inside Cursor when you don't need to. Get a Claude subscription instead and connect it to Cursor. Way cheaper. The token costs in Cursor add up fast if you're building anything substantial.

Exposing your API keys. Even if you store them in .env files, you can accidentally show them on screen. Happens all the time to people streaming or recording tutorials. Someone will find them. They will use your credits. Just... be paranoid about this one.

Using complicated frameworks for simple projects. Honestly, vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript will get you surprisingly far. Every framework you add is another thing the AI might mess up. Keep it simple until you have a reason not to.

Trusting the AI completely. Look, I get it. The whole point of vibe coding is to let go and let the AI handle things. But experienced developers don't actually do this. They guide the AI. They check its work. They stay in control. The term is catchy, but "vibe coding" is kind of a beginner mindset. Pros vibe a little, sure. But mostly they steer.

Tips That'll Make You Faster

Some of these might seem small. They're not.

Use your phone. This one surprised me. But think about it: you send a prompt, the AI works on it for a while, and you just... wait. Staring at your laptop. Instead, send the prompt from your phone, lock the screen, go do something else. Check back in ten minutes. The code's ready. Way less soul-crushing than watching a progress bar.

Plan outside, then import. There's this tool called Beads that helps with context management. The basic idea is useful even without the tool: do your thinking and planning in a separate document, get it clear, then bring it into your coding session. Keeps things cleaner.

Learn the keyboard shortcuts. In Claude Code, Shift+Tab cycles between brainstorming, planning, and coding modes. Sounds minor. Saves a ton of clicking around.

Install skills for better UI. Claude Code has these things called "skills" that improve specific capabilities. There are ones that make it way better at building user interfaces. The difference is noticeable. Default Claude builds kind of ugly blue and purple gradient stuff. With the right skill, it actually looks... decent?

The Tool Stack Most People Land On

You don't need much.

Claude Code or Cursor for the actual coding. Both work. Claude Code is simpler. Cursor has more features. Try both, see what clicks.

Claude Opus 4.5 as your model when you're doing anything complex. Yes, it's more expensive per token. Yes, it's worth it. The cheaper models work fine for simple stuff, but when you're building something real, Opus catches mistakes the others miss.

For research and feeding information to your AI, people use something called the MCP layer. Playwright for grabbing visual inspiration from websites, Perplexity for pulling information, Firecrawl for scraping. You probably don't need this right away. But good to know it exists when you're ready.

What Can You Actually Build With This?

More than you'd think.

People are building MVPs in under 24 hours. Full working products, not just mockups. Someone built a bot that scrapes Facebook pages, generates articles, and posts them automatically. Took about an hour.

Others are using it for creative stuff. Cinematic videos. Marketing assets. That surprised me too. It's not just code anymore.

The barrier is lower than it's ever been. If you can clearly describe what you want, you can probably build it. Or at least get 80% of the way there.

The Honest Truth

Vibe coding isn't going to replace actual developers anytime soon. The AI still makes mistakes. It still needs guidance. It still produces code that sometimes works but probably shouldn't.

But for getting an idea off the ground? For building tools for yourself? For prototyping something before you hire someone to build it properly?

It's kind of incredible.

You don't need to become a programmer. You just need to get good at communicating with one that never sleeps.

Start with one of those free courses. Build something small. See what happens.

Worst case, you waste a weekend. Best case, you have a new skill that might actually be useful.

If you haven't tried it, it might be worth your while.
